<h3><b>Short Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">If OPC_COND_EVT_LOG_SRC_PAT is set to TRUE, Logfile
Encapsulator enable pattern matching in the Source field of Windows EventLog
policy.<o:p></o:p></p>

<h3><b>Long Description</b></h3><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">The opcle agent is responsible for monitoring the Windows
Event log specified in the policy. The entries in the Windows Event log is
checked against the conditions in the policy. If condition is matched alert is
generated.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">Any windows event contains below properties:<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><ul><li>Computer: Name of the Server.</li><li>Source: Name of the process who created the event.</li><li>Category: Name of the task category of the event log.</li><li>Event ID: Value of the Event ID.</li><li>Type: Indicate the severity of the event log.</li></ul><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">We can create conditions in windows event log policy against
which above properties of any event will be compared for all incoming events. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">Variable OPC_COND_EVT_LOG_SRC_PAT implies if pattern
matching is allowed in Source condition of policy or not. If set to true we can
use pattern matching in Source condition of policy.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">Example:<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><ul><li>If value of OPC_COND_EVT_LOG_SRC_PAT is FALSE</li><ul><li>If one Windows Event log policy is having source field condition
with content as below: <br>“SQLAgent$&lt;*&gt;|MSSQL$&lt;*&gt;|MSSQLSERVER”</li><li>First incoming event:&nbsp;
Created by the process SQLAGENT$121 </li><li>Second incoming event: Created by the process MSSQLSERVER.</li><li>Due to disabled pattern matching in source condition of
policy, only second event will match the condition and alert will be generated
for second event only.</li></ul><li>If value of OPC_COND_EVT_LOG_SRC_PAT is TRUE</li><ul><li>If one Windows Event log policy is having source field
condition with content as below: “SQLAgent$&lt;*&gt;|MSSQL$&lt;*&gt;|MSSQLSERVER”</li><li>First incoming event: Created by the process SQLAGENT$121 </li><li>Second incoming event: Created by the process MSSQLSERVER.</li><li>As pattern matching is enabled in this case, both events
will match against policy condition and alert will be generated for both the
event.</li></ul></ul><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Use case:</b><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">When multiple instance of the same application is creating
events with slightly different source name. <o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">In such cases we can use pattern matching in source
condition of event log policy instead of creating different policies for
different instances of same application.<o:p></o:p></p>

<p class="MsoNormal">Example:</p><p class="MsoNormal">If SQLAGENT is having instance from SQLAGENT$1,
SQLAGENT$2,….SQLAGENT$150. By creating a single windows event log policy with
source field having “SQLAGENT$&lt;*&gt;”, opcle matches the condition for all
the instance of SQLAGENT.<o:p></o:p></p></div><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p></div><o:p></o:p><p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal">

















</p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p><p class="MsoNormal"><o:p></o:p></p>